      {
        "id": 2778484,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-12-24T15:31:07.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>From my cellar in France, this is still drinking well, with plenty of cedary cassis fruit overlaid with classic Mouton espresso-roast oak. There is a little tannic asperity on the finish that marks this out as an \u201cambitious\u201d effort in terms of extraction in a lighter vintage, but I am not going to fault the Ch\u00e2teau for trying.</p>\n<p>For me, \u201coff\u201d, or at least forgotten, 1970s vintages of Mouton are some of the best values in mature first growth claret, and I pick them up quite regularly for a very reasonable tariff. Not the sort of wines to take to tastings, but lovely over dinner at home for two.</p>",
